On Escalation Ticket # 00431776 the new comment has been added: Robert-Zoltan Sumi:

@WaitingOnEngineer Hi Ramon, according to the recording, the client is trying to upload files, which are already present on OneDrive server. Even if he deletes it, according to our experience, it could happen that OneDrive keeps them somewhere in a cache, and even if we block them, it restores from there. In the logs we report that they are blocked, therefore we must be sure that we really upload them. Can you repeat the test, with new files, which were never uploaded before to OneDrive? If we do not block them it would be helpful to have the logs. Please try to upload a single file at a given time, because the repeated upload tries generate too much noise.

[DevOps CommentId:11543296]

On Escalation Ticket # 00431776 the new comment has been added: Robert-Zoltan Sumi:

@WaitingOnEngineer Hi Ramon, I have watched the second recording too. As I see the client tried to upload a sample file from https://dlptest.endpointprotector.com. I have created a blocking policy with e-mail address as sensitive data, downloaded the sample file Name_DOB_Email.pdf and tried to upload to OneDrive from browser. I get a notification that is blocked, but it was uploaded. I renamed it, and it was uploaded again. However, if I try to upload a pdf created by me (exported from Microsoft Office) it is not uploaded. Please try to upload brand-new files with custom data to see if those files are uploaded or not.

